  "prompt": "The bond angle of Sulphur dioxide is greater than that of Ozone. Why?",
  "response": "The bond angle in sulfur dioxide (SO\u2082) is greater than that in ozone (O\u2083) due to differences in their molecular structures and the electronic environments around the central atoms.\n\n### 1. **Molecular Structure:**\n   - **Sulfur Dioxide (SO\u2082):** SO\u2082 has a bent (V-shaped) molecular geometry. The sulfur atom is at the center, bonded to two oxygen atoms, with one lone pair of electrons on sulfur. The bond angle in SO\u2082 is approximately **119\u00b0**.\n   - **Ozone (O\u2083):** O\u2083 also has a bent (V-shaped) molecular geometry. The central oxygen atom is bonded to two other oxygen atoms, with one lone pair of electrons on the central oxygen. The bond angle in O\u2083 is approximately **117\u00b0**.\n\n### 2. **Electronic Environment:**\n   - **Sulfur Dioxide (SO\u2082):** The sulfur atom in SO\u2082 has a larger atomic size and lower electronegativity compared to oxygen. The sulfur atom can accommodate the lone pair of electrons more effectively, and the bonding pairs are less repelled by the lone pair. This results in a slightly larger bond angle.\n   - **Ozone (O\u2083):** The central oxygen atom in O\u2083 has a smaller atomic size and higher electronegativity compared to sulfur. The lone pair of electrons on the central oxygen exerts a stronger repulsion on the bonding pairs, causing the bond angle to be slightly smaller.\n\n### 3. **Lone Pair Repulsion:**\n   - In both molecules, the lone pair of electrons on the central atom causes electron repulsion, which tends to compress the bond angles. However, because sulfur is larger and less electronegative than oxygen, the lone pair in SO\u2082 has less of a compressing effect on the bond angle compared to the lone pair in O\u2083.\n\n### Conclusion:\nThe bond angle in sulfur dioxide (SO\u2082) is greater than that in ozone (O\u2083) primarily because sulfur\u2019s larger size and lower electronegativity lead to less repulsion from the lone pair, allowing the bond angle to open up more compared to the situation in ozone where the central oxygen\u2019s smaller size and higher electronegativity result in a slightly compressed bond angle.",
